# Control an LED using push buttons


## 1. Overview

In this lesson, you are going to learn how to use two push buttons to control
the brightness of an LED.

## 2. Components required

* Development board
* Breadboard 830p
* 2 x push buttons
* 1 x LED
* 1 x 150 Ω resistor
* 7 x male-to-male jumper wires
* Micro USB – Type A USB cable

## 3. Connections

  Below you can find the schematic:

In the next diagram we have as main elements the button and the led. 
  
  The buttons will have 2 connections, one with the ground and one like a pin on the board. 
  The connected pins must be diagonal to avoid a short circuit. 
  
  The LED needs to attach a resistor to the cathode to avoid damage.
  
  Next, you can find a visual representation of the project:

## 4. Code

### Import libraries
First, we import libraries to later use the functions and variables predefined in them.

#use these libraries to declare used pins and PWM
from machine import Pin, PWM
#for delay
from time import sleep

### Declaration variables
The code starts with the declaration of the pins used by the buttons and the LED. 

We fisrt declare as an input pins ('Pin.IN') and also as an pull up pins ('Pin.PULL_UP') the two buttons and as output pin ('Pin.OUT') the led.

Led is connected to D7 (GPIO**13**), the button that will reduce the brightness is connected to D1 (GPIO**5**) and the button for increasing the brightness is connected to D2 (GPIO**4**).

#define the pins used by the buttons and led
#also initialise it as INPUT, PULL_UP and led as OUTPUT
button_down = Pin(5, Pin.IN, Pin.PULL_UP)
button_up = Pin(4,  Pin.IN, Pin.PULL_UP)
led = Pin(13, Pin.OUT)

We declare the pwm for led to create fluctuating energy.

Also, we need an integer variable that will store a value from 0 (0%
duty cycle) to 1023 (100% duty cycle).

#declare the pwm for led 
pwm = PWM(led)

#the integer variable that is initially null
container = 0

### Infinite loop

We will create an infinite loop ('while True') for the board to execute the instructions continuously.

In the this while loop we have also two while loops, one for each button. 

When the down button is pressed, an if statement will change the value of container, and turn on the LED at the new value. Also, we will need a delay, in this case we have chosen 10 ms, between runs.

#for board execute the instructions continuously we make an infinite loop
while True:
    #while the down button is pressed
    while button_down.value() == 0:
        #the minimum value for container is 0, so if the
        #value is greater than 50, we can substract 50
        #else, the value will be set to 0
        print('Button down pressed')
        if container > 50:
            #change the value
            container = container - 50
        else:
            #set the value to 0
            container = 0;
        
        #turn on the LED
        pwm.duty(container)
        #wait 10 ms before the next run
        sleep(0.1)
        
    #while the up button is pressed
    while button_up.value() == 0: 
        #the maximum value for container is 1023
        #if the value is less than 972, we can add 50
        #otherwise, the container will be set to 1023
        print('Button up pressed')
        if container < 972:
            container = container + 50
        else:
            container = 1023
        
        #turn on the LED
        pwm.duty(container)  # =analogWrite (din arduino)
        #wait 10 ms before the next run
        sleep(0.1)

Next step is to gently connect the development board to the computer via the
included micro USB cable. There is only one way to plug it in, do not use force to
insert the cable.

To compile the code you should follow the instructions for the board *Adafruit CLUE* from this link:
https://youtu.be/F_4GXU8kKfk?t=585

**Congratulations**, you have completed the tutorial!
